TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ben-David, Itzhak
AU  - Hirshleifer, David
T1  - Are Investors Really Reluctant to Realize Their Losses? Trading Responses to Past Returns and the Disposition Effect
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhs077
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 8
SP  - 2485
EP  - 2532
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We examine how investor preferences and beliefs affect trading in relation to past gains and losses. The probability of selling as a function of profit is V-shaped; at short holding periods, investors are more likely to sell big losers than small ones. There is little evidence of an upward jump in selling at zero profits. These findings provide no clear indication that realization preference explains trading. Furthermore, the disposition effect is not driven by a simple direct preference for selling a stock by virtue of having a gain versus a loss. Trading based on belief revisions can potentially explain these findings.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhs077
ER  - 



